<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-895-850  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 895 850.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 6 1989 v217 n20 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Statesboro Tel sees the light. (Statesboro Telephone Co.; fiberoptic system replaces copper-based analog)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harville, Rodney.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Statesboro Telephone Co, an independent teleco serving 13,000customers, replaces an ageing copper-based analog system with afiber optic system that boosts traffic capacity and transmissionquality.andP;  The new cable has four single-mode optical fibers - asend/receive pair and a back-up pair.andP;  Fibers are joined by fusionsplicing.andP;  Several measures ensure service reliability.andP;  A pair oflong-range cable-locating systems installed at the central officeand remote interface helps quickly determine whether a planned digwill hit the cable.andP;  A PSI Telecommunications Inc Lightlinkerfiber optic splicer is on hand for emergency repairs.andP;  Emergencyrestoration kits containing 300-foot lengths of cable are on hand.andO;Since this 1987 installation, Statesboro has constructed a secondfiber optic system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Statesboro Telephone Company Inc. (services).andO;Topic:     Telephone systemsCommunications CircuitsCommunications ApplicationsTelecommunicationsFiber opticsTelephone Companies.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>